ed, temporary, and often, illusory.\n\n- Matthieu Ricard, Happiness: A Guide to Developing Life's Most Important Skill\n|\nI’m happy. But some beauty is nonesuch - The gently sloping path across the wood, The wretched bridge that’s just a little skewed And that, for which, I won’t be waiting much.\n\n- Anna Akhmatova, White Flock\n|\nUnless you are free from your own mind, you can never truly experience the freedom with life.\n\n- Roshan\n|\nNot all things can be expressed through words, not all the words reflect the truth.\n\n- Ary\n|\nThere is little more I can add short of dissecting the man, or going into intimate details such as the modest proportions and slight southeasterly curvature of his manhood.\n\n- Félix J. Palma, The Map of Time\n|\n. . . there is a wish in the heart of mankind to be distracted and confused. Truth is but one attraction, and not always the most powerful.\n\n- Joyce\n|\nClearly I miss Him, having been brought up in religion. But now a man must be responsible to himself.\n\n- Ernest Hemingway, For Whom the Bell Tolls\n|\nOh dear Sunday, I am so happy that I want your entire wisdom at my dinner table.\n\n- Santosh\n|\n...[M]y inner self moved; my spirit shook its always-fettered wings half loose. I had a sudden feeling as if I, who never yet truly lived, were at last about to taste life.\n\n- Charlotte Brontë, Villette\n|\nIt is not my words that I polish, but my ideas. 102\n\n- Joseph Joubert, The Notebooks of Joseph Joubert\n|\nWhen you know your role in life, living makes sense because of clarity, and the loads become enjoyable to carry.\n\n- Innocent Mwatsikesimbe, The Vision\n|\nWhether we like it or not, the one justification for the existence of all religions is death, they need death as much as we need bread to eat.\n\n- José Saramago, Death with Interruptions\n|\nIf our foundation is on God,then our burden becomes His and we sail through smoothly.\n\n- Latika\n|\nWhen I discovered libraries, it was like having Christmas every day.